Machine Learning Method Comparison

Introduction

The goal of this final project is to predict the interest rate of a loan, based off various payment and income information. This dataset includes all loan data for all loans issued by Lending Club from 2007 to 2019, comprising over 2 million observations. Due to computing constraints, the analysis to the first 10,000 observations. With this data, I will explore the regression methods we learned this quarter, as well as their sensitivity to the different test-train data splits.

Data Cleaning

Our dataset has many variables that caused instances of high linear dependance or other errors when designing our models, so we only kept variables that we though would be pertinent to our study.

loans = read.csv("loan.csv", nrows = 10000)

Remove columns from dataset that have missing values in at least half the rows of the dataset. Also remove columns from data set where the values of each row are all the same.

loans = loans[, colSums(is.na(loans)) < nrow(loans)/2]
loans = Filter(function(x) length(unique(x))>1, loans)

Keep columns that we believe to be pertinent to interest rate and not linearly dependent. Also removed rows with N/A.

loans=loans[ , which(names(loans) %in% c("funded_amnt", "term", "int_rate", "emp_length", "home_ownership", "annual_inc", "verification_status",  "purpose", "delinq_2yrs", "earliest_cr_line", "open_acc", "pub_rec", "revol_bal", "initial_list_status", "acc_open_past_24mths", "avg_cur_bal", "num_sats", "pub_rec_bankruptcies"))]

# turn date format into an int
dates = paste('01', loans$earliest_cr_line)
loans$earliest_cr_line = as.Date(dates, format = "%d %b-%Y")
loans$earliest_cr_line = as.integer(loans$earliest_cr_line)

# emp_length had some N/A stored as a string
loans = loans[!(loans$emp_length=="n/a"),]
loans$emp_length = factor(loans$emp_length)
loans = na.omit(loans)

Variable Selection

For variable selection, we tested four different methods, Forwards stepwise, Backwards stepwise, Ridge regression, and LASSO. For Ridge regression and LASSO, we used cross validation in order to find the best value of \(\lambda\).

set.seed(2)
loans = na.omit(loans)
train = sample(nrow(loans), nrow(loans)/2)
loans_train=loans[train,]
loans_test=loans[-train,]

Forward stepwise

predict.regsubsets =function (object ,newdata ,id ,...){
form=as.formula (object$call [[2]])
mat=model.matrix (form ,newdata )
coefi =coef(object ,id=id)
xvars =names (coefi )
mat[,xvars ]%*% coefi
}

forwardm = regsubsets(int_rate~., data = loans_train, method = "forward", nvmax = ncol(loans)-1)
## Warning in leaps.setup(x, y, wt = wt, nbest = nbest, nvmax = nvmax, force.in =
## force.in, : 1 linear dependencies found
val.errors = rep(NA, ncol(loans)-1)
for (i in 1:(ncol(loans)-1)) {
    pred = predict.regsubsets(forwardm, loans_test, i)
    val.errors[i] = mean((loans_test$int_rate - pred)^2)
}
min(val.errors)
## [1] 19.46113

Backward stepwise

backwardm = regsubsets(int_rate~., data = loans_train, method = "backward", nvmax = ncol(loans)-1)
## Warning in leaps.setup(x, y, wt = wt, nbest = nbest, nvmax = nvmax, force.in =
## force.in, : 1 linear dependencies found
val.errors = rep(NA, ncol(loans)-1)
for (i in 1:(ncol(loans)-1)) {
    pred = predict.regsubsets(backwardm, loans_test, i)
    val.errors[i] = mean((loans_test$int_rate - pred)^2)
}

min(val.errors)
## [1] 19.53017

Ridge Regression

library(glmnet)

x = model.matrix(int_rate ~ ., loans)[,-1]
y = loans$int_rate

cv.out = cv.glmnet(x[train,], y[train], alpha = 0)
bestlam = cv.out$lambda.min
ridgem = glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha =0, lambda =bestlam)
ridge.pred = predict(ridgem, s = bestlam, newx = x[-train,])
mean((y[-train] - ridge.pred)^2)
## [1] 19.50978

LASSO

cv.out = cv.glmnet(x[train,], y[train], alpha = 1)
bestlam = cv.out$lambda.min
lassom = glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha =1, lambda =bestlam)
lasso.pred = predict(lassom, s = bestlam, newx = x[-train,])
mean((y[-train] - lasso.pred)^2)
## [1] 19.50922

Forward Stepwise ended up returning the lowest test error at about 19.46 followed by LASSO and Ridge Regression at 19.51 and the stepwise backwards at 19.53. All methods return very similar test errors, so using any method should probably be acceptable. For our own varaible reduction method, we are going to use the forwards subset selection because it returned the best test error.

Model exploration

First we create 3 training sets at sizes 500, 1000, and 4591 (half the total dataset) and their repsective test sets.

set.seed(2)
loans = na.omit(loans)
trainsm = sample(nrow(loans), 500)

#filtering out variables that are not in both test and train data
loans = filter(loans, home_ownership != 'ANY')
loans = filter(loans, !purpose %in% c('house', 'renewable_energy', 'moving'))


loans_trainsm=loans[trainsm,]
loans_testsm=loans[-trainsm,]
trainsm = sample(nrow(loans), 500)
loans_trainsm=loans[trainsm,]
loans_testsm=loans[-trainsm,]

trainmed=sample(nrow(loans), 1000)
loans_trainmed=loans[trainmed,]
loans_testmed=loans[-trainmed,]

trainlar = sample(nrow(loans), nrow(loans)/2)
loans_trainlar=loans[trainlar,]
loans_testlar=loans[-trainlar,]

In these models the test error rate was not particulary sensitive to the size of the training data, all though there were small changes. The medium sized training data model performed the best, followed by the small and the largest.

Polynomial Regression

poly_degrees = c(2,3,5,10)
cv.error = rep(0,4)
for (i in 1:4){
  glm.fit = glm(data = loans, int_rate~poly(funded_amnt, poly_degrees[i])+ poly(annual_inc,poly_degrees[i])+poly(delinq_2yrs, poly_degrees[i]) + poly(earliest_cr_line, poly_degrees[i])+ poly(revol_bal, poly_degrees[i])+ poly(acc_open_past_24mths, poly_degrees[i])+poly(num_sats, poly_degrees[i]) + term + home_ownership + verification_status+purpose+initial_list_status)
  cv.error[i] = cv.glm(loans, glmfit = glm.fit, K=5)$delta[1]
}
cv.error

For the polynomial models, there were drastic changes in test error as the size of the training data changed. While the model with the most training error performed at a similar error rate to previous models, both the smaller models had very larger training errors, and likely would perfom better for a lower polynomial degree.

GAM

We can fit a general additive model using splines to our model Since we determined that only annual_inc may have a non-linear relation ship with int_rate, we can fit it with a smoothing spline and add it to our model

GAM n = 500

gam_small = gam(int_rate ~ funded_amnt + term + home_ownership + s(annual_inc, df = 4) + verification_status + purpose + delinq_2yrs + earliest_cr_line + revol_bal + initial_list_status + acc_open_past_24mths + num_sats, data = loans_trainsm)

Boosting

For boosting, the optimal tuning parameter lambda is determined through cross validation.

Boosting n = 500

set.seed(1)
lambda.seq = seq(from = .01, to = .05, by = .01)
trees.seq = seq(from = 500, to =  1000, by = 100)
depth.seq = seq(from=1, to = 5, by  = 1)
index= 0
test.errs = numeric(125)

for (i in 1:length(lambda.seq)) {
  for(j in 1: length(trees.seq)){
    for(k in 1:length(depth.seq)){
      combo = c(lambda.seq[i], trees.seq[j], depth.seq[k])
      index = index +1 
    boost.interest = gbm(int_rate~., data = loans_trainsm, distribution = "gaussian",
                         n.trees = trees.seq[j], shrinkage = lambda.seq[i], interaction.depth = depth.seq[k])
    yhat.boost = predict(boost.interest, newdata = loans_testsm, n.trees = trees.seq[j])
    test.errs[index] = mean((yhat.boost - loans_testsm$int_rate)^2)
  }
}
}
#plot(lambda.seq, test.errs, type = "b")

tab_matrix = matrix(nrow = 3, ncol = 2)
colnames(tab_matrix) = c("lambda", "test error")
rownames(tab_matrix) = c("training n=500", "training n=1000", "training n=4591")
tab_matrix[1,1] = lambda.seq[which.min(test.errs)]
tab_matrix[1,2] = min(test.errs)


which.min(test.errs)
## [1] 2
boostsmte = min(test.errs)
boostsmte
## [1] 19.20454

For the small training set, the best lambda is 0.02 and it has a test error of 20.06.

                         n.trees = 1000, shrinkage = lambda.seq[i])

KNN and Principal Components Regression

I wanted to include a note on these two models, as they were among the ones we considered for analysis. As these are generally not possible with categorical variables of many factors, and we had multiple variables with many categorical levels, we determined KNN and PC Regression were not suitable models for our dataset.

Comparison visualization

In this comparison, the shortcomings of the polynomial regression are eye-catching. This is perhaps unfair to the the merits of including polynomial terms, but does strongly show the dangers of overfitting with exponentia

Removing Polynomial Regression to give the other bars appropriate scale:

ggplot(data = results[-c(4,5,6),]) + geom_bar(aes(x = Models, y = testerrors, fill = Size), position = 'dodge', stat = 'identity') + labs(x = 'Type of Model', y = 'Avg Test Error')+ scale_fill_discrete(name = 'Size of Training Data')

Conclusion

With all of our models, we had a range of test errors from to 18.7 to over 250. Overall, the GAM and boosting models performed the best across the three sizes of our training data in the c. The models with less training data tended to have higher test errors, and were especially high when using models with large variance, such as polynomials. Models with higher interpretability and a more visual form, such as regular trees and neural networks had test error rates of around 10-20% higher than more standard models, but are likely easier to explain. The test errror rates on average declined as the size. Overall, the varying results in this project for different models, tuning parameters, and training data sizes show the importance of trying multiple approaches to analysis in order to have comprehensive analysis.
